✨ Realisation-

Forward logic: It first checked the last digit, then nested a carry loop. It works, but it’s a bit verbose.
Backward optimal logic: Realised I can collapse that into one clean backward loop:
If a digit < 9, increment and return immediately.
If it’s 9, set to 0 and keep carrying left.
If all digits are 9, allocate a new array with one extra slot and set the first digit to 1.

✅ Why It’s Optimal-

Single pass: Only one backward loop, no nested structures.
Early exit: As soon as a digit < 9 is found, you stop.
Elegant handling: The all-9s case is neatly handled at the end.
Time complexity: 𝑂(𝑛) worst case, but often exits much earlier.
Space complexity: 𝑂(1) extra space, except when a new array is needed.
